title: For Sale:  Russian VEPR AK 7.62x39 Plus Extras
postcontent: I am selling my converted 7.62x39 Russian Molot VEPR. A VEPR is one of two authentic Russian AK's still being made today, Siaga's being the other. The VEPR's are made by Molot which is the factory that made soviet era light machine guns called RPK's for the soviet military. RPK's are just like an AK except they have a thicker reciever and barrel. VEPR's are known for being built like tanks and generally unkillable. The are imported into the US in a sporter configuration with a thumbhole stock and unable to take standard AK magazines. I have converted this one to take standard magazines and added a folding stock and muzzle brake. Everything the gun has and comes with:Manticore arms aluminum triangle stockStormwerkz folding adapterAce style stock adapterI modified the grip off the thumbole stock and made it a pistol gripHas a tapco slotted muzzle brakeInstalled a bullet guide so it takes standard AK magazinesHas a krebbs custom rear apature sight, i still have the facory notch sight tooComes with:17 tapco polymer 30 round magazines15 surplus steel 30 round magazinesThe facory 5 and 10 round magazinesAbout 700 rounds of Golden Tiger 7.62x39 (awesome stuff)120 rounds of tulammoA chinese surplus sks slingFactory cleaning rod

postcontent: This D. Moore Model 1860 7 Shot single action .32 Short caliber revolver is in very good working condition. The Moore Revolver was the first "swing out" rear loading cartridge revolver. Very popuar during the Civil war with Union and Confederate Soldiers alike. A Confederate soldier's body was unearthed from a shallow grave at Gettysburg, holding a Moore 7 Shot revolver, with 3 rounds still loaded in the cylinder. Moore was sued by Smith and Wesson on a patent infringement and was forced to include on all Model 1860's made after 1862 "Mfd by Moore Arms Co. New York, for Smith and Wesson Co,"(something of that nature") This particular firearm, was made before the lawsuit and reads only "D, Moore Patent, Sept. 18, 1860"...only about 3000 of the just over 7000 Moore Model 1860s bear those markings.This firearm is fully functional!!(SHOOT AT YOUR OWN RISK!!!)
